'''Taiwanese units of measurement''' ({{zh|t=臺制|p=Táizhì|poj=Tâi-chè}}) are the customary and traditional [[Units of measurement|units of measure]] used in [[Taiwan]].  Many of the units derive from [[Japanese units of measurement]] and have similar names as [[Chinese units of measurement]] but different conversions than in [[mainland China]] or [[Hong Kong]].  In some cases these units are used exclusively, in some cases alongside official [[International System of Units|metric (SI)]] units, and in other cases they have been supplanted by metric units.  [[Linguistics|Linguistically]], practically all Taiwanese units of measure are [[Chinese classifier]]s used to [[classifier (linguistics)|classify]] [[nouns]].

==Length==
Linear measure in Taiwan is largely metric but some units derived from traditional Japanese units of measurement remain in use as a legacy of [[Taiwan under Japanese rule|Japanese rule]].

{|  class="wikitable"
! Unit || Definition || Basis
|-
| 1 Taiwanese inch ({{zh|c={{linktext|寸}}|p=cùn|poj=chhùn|labels=no}}) || 3.030{{nbsp}}cm || Japanese ''[[Cun (unit)|sun]]''
|-
| 1 Taiwanese foot ({{zh|c={{linktext|尺}}|p=chǐ|poj=chhioh|labels=no}}) || 30.30{{nbsp}}cm || Japanese ''[[Shaku (unit)|shaku]]''
|}

==Area==
[[File:10-Phêng Apartment.JPG|thumb|200px|An advertisement from [[IKEA]] for a 10-''ping'' apartment]]

Unlike with other measures, area continues to be almost commonly measured with traditional units. The principal unit for measuring the floorspace of an office or apartment, the ''ping'' ({{zh|c={{linktext|坪}}|p=píng|poj=pêⁿ / pîⁿ / phêⁿ / phîⁿ / phiâⁿ / phêng|labels=no}}) derives from the Japanese ''[[Japanese units of measurement#Area|tsubo]]'', the base unit of the Japanese area. Taiwanese units of [[land measurement]] derive from both traditional [[Dutch units of measurement|Dutch]] and Japanese measurements.  The principal unit of land measure, the ''jia'' ({{zh|c={{linktext|甲}}|p=jiǎ|poj=kah|labels=no}}), derives from the obsolete Dutch ''[[morgen]]'', which was introduced during Taiwan's [[Dutch Formosa|Dutch era]]. The ''li'' ({{zh|c={{linktext|犁}}|p=lí|poj=lê|labels=no}}) represented the area that could be farmed by one man with one ox and one plow in one day.

*1&nbsp;''ping'' = 36&nbsp;square ''chi'' = {{convert|3.306|m2|ft2|abbr=on}}
*1&nbsp;''mu'' ({{zh|c={{linktext|畝}}|p=mǔ|poj=bó͘|labels=no}}) = 30&nbsp;''ping'' = {{convert|99.2|m2|ft2|abbr=on}}
*1&nbsp;''jia'' = 2,934&nbsp;''ping'' = {{convert|0.9699|hectare|acre}}{{sfnp|MOE|2011|loc=#1857}}
*1&nbsp;''li'' = 5&nbsp;''jia''  = {{convert|4.8496|hectare|acre}}

Officially, land area is measured in [[hectare]]s and [[square kilometer]]s.<ref>{{cite web|script-title=zh:《中華民國統計資訊網》縣市重要統計指標查詢系統網|url=http://statdb.dgbas.gov.tw/pxweb/Dialog/statfile9.asp|accessdate=25 July 2016|language=zh}}</ref>

==Volume==
Volume measure in Taiwan is largely metric, with common units such as liter and milliliter.

{{Expand section|date=June 2008}}

==Mass==
[[Image:Sam-ho-chhi.jpg|thumb|Fruit sold in [[catty|catties]] in a Taiwanese market]]
Packaged goods in Taiwan largely use metric measurements but bulk foodstuffs sold in [[wet market]]s and [[supermarket]]s are typically measured with units derived from traditional [[Japanese_units_of_measurement#Mass|Japanese units of mass]], which are similar but not equivalent to corresponding [[Chinese_units_of_measurement#Mass|Chinese units of mass]]. 

*1&nbsp;[[Cash (unit)|cash]] ({{zh|c=釐|p=lí|poj=lî|labels=no}}) = 37.5&nbsp;[[milligram|mg]]
*1&nbsp;[[candareen]] ({{zh|c=分|p=fēn|poj=hun|labels=no}}) = 10&nbsp;cash = 375&nbsp;mg
*1&nbsp;[[Mace (measurement)|mace]] ({{zh|c=錢|p=qián|poj=chîⁿ|labels=no}}) = 10&nbsp;candareens = 3.75&nbsp;[[gram|g]]
*1&nbsp;[[tael#Taiwan|tael]] ({{zh|c=兩|p=liǎng|poj=niú|labels=no}}) = 10&nbsp;mace = 37.5&nbsp;g
*1&nbsp;[[catty]] ({{zh|c=斤|p=jīn|poj=kin/kun|labels=no}}) = 16&nbsp;taels = 0.6&nbsp;[[kilogram|kg]]
*1&nbsp;[[picul]] ({{zh|c=擔|p=dān|poj=tàⁿ|labels=no}}) = 100&nbsp;catties = 60&nbsp;kg
Note the tael and catty are widely used.

